 DHCP Configuration and Management on Fedora 

1. Install the DHCP server package
sudo dnf install dhcp-server -y


2. Edit the DHCP configuration file
sudo nano /etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf


Example configuration for network `192.168.193.0/24`:

option domain-name "localdomain";
option domain-name-servers 8.8.8.8, 8.8.4.4;

default-lease-time 600;
max-lease-time 7200;
authoritative;

subnet 192.168.193.0 netmask 255.255.255.0 {
    range 192.168.193.100 192.168.193.200;
    option routers 192.168.193.1;
    option subnet-mask 255.255.255.0;
}

* Subnet: `192.168.193.0/24`
* Range: `192.168.193.100 – 192.168.193.200`
* Router/Gateway: `192.168.193.1`
* DNS: Google DNS (8.8.8.8, 8.8.4.4)

3. Save and exit nano
* CTRL + O → save
* Enter → confirm filename
* CTRL + X → exit

4. Start and enable the DHCP service
sudo systemctl enable --now dhcpd

5. Allow DHCP through firewall
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=FedoraServer --add-service=dhcp --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

6. Verify firewall services
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=FedoraServer --list-all
You should see:
services: cockpit dhcpv6-client ssh http https dhcp

7. Check DHCP service status
systemctl status dhcpd

8. View DHCP leases
   DHCP leases are stored in:
/var/lib/dhcpd/dhcpd.leases

To monitor logs:
journalctl -u dhcpd

 when you check the DHCP logs, you’re looking at a record of:
Which IP addresses were assigned to which clients
When leases started or expired
Any errors or warnings about the DHCP service


 and with this configuration, Fedora now acts as a DHCP server, handing out IPs in the range `192.168.193.100–200` to clients on my network.
Added Fedora DHCP setup guide

